The paper proposes a new algorithm for estimating the parameters of Gaussian mixture models, which are commonly used in machine learning and computer vision. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.LG (Machine Learning), cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also discusses the relationship between the negative log-likelihood function and the Kullback-Leibler divergence, which suggests a possible connection to information theory and coding. Therefore, cs.IT (Information Theory) is also a likely sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a stochastic gradient descent scheme to optimize the sliced-Wasserstein distance, which involves numerical optimization and could be related to numerical analysis and optimization, making cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) a possible sub-category as well.
